    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Amortized Analysis Demonstration</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            line-height: 1.6;\n            max-width: 800px;\n            margin: 0 auto;\n            padding: 20px;\n        }\n        h1, h2 {\n            color: #2c3e50;\n        }\n        .container {\n            background-color: #f9f9f9;\n            border-radius: 8px;\n            padding: 20px;\n            margin-bottom: 20px;\n        }\n        button {\n            background-color: #3498db;\n            color: white;\n            border: none;\n            padding: 10px 15px;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            cursor: pointer;\n            margin-right: 10px;\n        }\n        button:hover {\n            background-color: #2980b9;\n        }\n        .output {\n            margin-top: 20px;\n            padding: 15px;\n            background-color: #ecf0f1;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            font-family: monospace;\n            white-space: pre-wrap;\n            min-height: 100px;\n        }\n        table {\n            width: 100%;\n            border-collapse: collapse;\n            margin: 15px 0;\n        }\n        th, td {\n            border: 1px solid #ddd;\n            padding: 8px;\n            text-align: left;\n        }\n        th {\n            background-color: #f2f2f2;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>Amortized Analysis Demonstration</h1>\n    \n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <h2>What is Amortized Analysis?</h2>\n        <p>\n            Amortized analysis is a method for analyzing a sequence of operations where, while some individual operations may be expensive, \n            the average cost per operation is small when averaged over the entire sequence. It provides a worst-case guarantee on the average \n            performance of each operation in the worst case.\n        </p>\n        <p>\n            This is different from average-case analysis because we're not making any probabilistic assumptions - the amortized analysis \n            guarantees that any sequence of operations will have the stated average cost.\n        </p>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <h2>Dynamic Array Example</h2>\n        <p>\n            A common example is a dynamic array that grows when it becomes full. While some append operations may be expensive (when resizing is needed), \n            the average cost per append operation is constant (O(1) amortized time).\n        </p>\n        \n        <button onclick=\"runSimulation()\">Run Simulation</button>\n        <button onclick=\"clearOutput()\">Clear Output</button>\n        \n        <div class=\"output\" id=\"output\">Results will appear here...</div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <h2>Three Methods of Amortized Analysis</h2>\n        \n        <h3>1. Aggregate Method</h3>\n        <p>\n            Determine total cost of n operations, then divide by n to get average cost per operation.\n        </p>\n        \n        <h3>2. Accounting Method</h3>\n        <p>\n            Assign different charges to each operation (\"amortized cost\"). Some operations are overcharged to cover future expensive operations.\n        </p>\n        \n        <h3>3. Potential Method</h3>\n        <p>\n            Define a \"potential\" function on the data structure's state. The amortized cost is the actual cost plus the change in potential.\n        </p>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <h2>Amortized Analysis of Dynamic Array</h2>\n        <p>When the array is full, we:</p>\n        <ol>\n            <li>Allocate a new array of double the size (cost: n operations)</li>\n            <li>Copy all elements to the new array (cost: n operations)</li>\n            <li>Add the new element (cost: 1 operation)</li>\n        </ol>\n        <p>Total cost for this operation: 2n + 1</p>\n        <p>But the next n-1 operations will only cost 1 each.</p>\n        <p>Total cost for n operations: (2n + 1) + (n - 1) = 3n</p>\n        <p>Amortized cost per operation: 3n / n = 3 (which is O(1))</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <script>\n        function runSimulation() {\n            const output = document.getElementById('output');\n            output.innerHTML = \"Running dynamic array simulation...\\n\\n\";\n            \n            let array = [];\n            let capacity = 1;\n            let totalCost = 0;\n            let totalOperations = 0;\n            let results = [];\n            \n            // Initial array allocation\n            array = new Array(capacity);\n            array[0] = 0;  // First element\n            totalCost += 1;  // Cost of insertion\n            totalOperations += 1;\n            results.push({\n                operation: 1,\n                action: \"Insert 0\",\n                size: 1,\n                capacity: capacity,\n                cost: 1,\n                totalCost: totalCost,\n                amortizedCost: (totalCost / totalOperations).toFixed(2)\n            });\n            \n            // Insert 19 more elements (total 20)\n            for (let i = 1; i < 20; i++) {\n                let cost = 1;  // Base cost of insertion\n                \n                // Check if we need to resize\n                if (i >= capacity) {\n                    let oldCapacity = capacity;\n                    capacity *= 2;  // Double the capacity\n                    \n                    // Cost of copying old elements to new array\n                    cost += oldCapacity;\n                    // Cost of allocating new array (simplified as 1 operation)\n                    cost += 1;\n                    \n                    output.innerHTML += `Resizing from ${oldCapacity} to ${capacity} (cost: ${cost})\\n`;\n                }\n                \n                array[i] = i;  // Insert element\n                totalCost += cost;\n                totalOperations += 1;\n                \n                results.push({\n                    operation: i + 1,\n                    action: `Insert ${i}`,\n                    size: i + 1,\n                    capacity: capacity,\n                    cost: cost,\n                    totalCost: totalCost,\n                    amortizedCost: (totalCost / totalOperations).toFixed(2)\n                });\n            }\n            \n            // Display results in a table\n            let table = \"<table><tr><th>Operation</th><th>Action</th><th>Size</th><th>Capacity</th><th>Cost</th><th>Total Cost</th><th>Amortized Cost</th></tr>\";\n            \n            results.forEach(row => {\n                table += `<tr>\n                    <td>${row.operation}</td>\n                    <td>${row.action}</td>\n                    <td>${row.size}</td>\n                    <td>${row.capacity}</td>\n                    <td>${row.cost}</td>\n                    <td>${row.totalCost}</td>\n                    <td>${row.amortizedCost}</td>\n                </tr>`;\n            });\n            \n            table += \"</table>\";\n            \n            output.innerHTML += \"\\nSimulation Results:\\n\";\n            output.innerHTML += table;\n            \n            output.innerHTML += `\\nFinal amortized cost: ${(totalCost / totalOperations).toFixed(2)} per operation (approaches O(1))`;\n        }\n        \n        function clearOutput() {\n            document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = \"Results will appear here...\";\n        }\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
  },
